## 3. Routing Constraints by Group

### 3.1 JESD204B GTH SERDES Lanes (8 pairs, 16 nets + caps)

**Preferred routing layer: In2.Cu (layer 2, signal).**
Rationale: In2.Cu is sandwiched between In1.Cu (GND) above and In3.Cu (GND)
below, providing dual solid ground references — the optimal configuration for
stripline at JESD204B frequencies. Per ADRV9009 DS p113:
> "on an 8-layer board, use Layer 7 for the stripline pair" (ADRV9009-W/PCBZ
> layer numbering; equivalent to our In2.Cu in a GND–Signal–GND sandwich).

Alternate layer: In5.Cu is acceptable for lower-priority lanes, but its
reference planes are In4.Cu (power) above and In6.Cu (GND) below — asymmetric;
avoid for JESD unless In2.Cu is congested.

| Constraint | Value | Source |
|---|---|---|
| Zdiff | 100 Ω ± 10% | ADRV9009 DS Rev B p113 |
| ZO (each conductor) | 50 Ω | ADRV9009 DS Rev B p112 |
| Coupling style | Loosely coupled (not tightly coupled) | ADRV9009 DS Rev B Figure 444 |
| Intra-pair skew (P-N mismatch) | ≤ 5 mil (127 µm) | **[DERIVED — NO MANDATORY SPEC]** UG576 v1.7.1 §5 and DS925 GTH DC specs (p421) both searched 2026-06-23; neither gives a PCB P/N routing length constraint. DS925 TOSKEW ≤ 10 ps is the chip TX output intrapair skew (silicon spec, not PCB routing rule). Derived bound: keep ≤ 10–15 ps (< 1/8 UI at 12.288 Gbps; 1 UI = 81.4 ps) → ≤ 60–90 mil FR4 (170 ps/in). ≤ 5 mil is well within this — conservative good practice. |
| Inter-lane length match | **[VERIFIED — NOT BOARD-BINDING]** | CHAN_BOND_MAX_SKEW=1 (ADI util_adxcvr_xch.v lines 560/1064/1842/2724; UG576 §4 p287). At 12.288 Gbps / 40-bit: USRCLK ≈ 307 MHz → 1 cycle = 3.26 ns → ≈ 19 in FR4. Any carrier inter-lane mismatch is negligible vs. this limit. Good-practice target: ≤ 100–200 mil within a lane group. Caveat: if JESD204B subclass 1 deterministic latency required, verify subclass setting in ADI JESD IP config (Vivado IP GUI or .xci) before routing. |
| Max trace length | < 6 inches (152 mm) preferred | ADRV9009 DS p113: "for distances > 6 in, use premium material" |
| PCB material note | Standard FR4 acceptable if total path ≤ 6 in | ADRV9009 DS p113 |
| Reference plane | Unbroken GND on both adjacent layers for full trace length | ADRV9009 DS p112 |
| Via count | Minimize; use back-drilled or blind vias if possible | ADRV9009 DS p113 |
| Via ground stitching | GND via pair adjacent to each signal via pair | ADRV9009 DS p113 |
| Inter-lane isolation | Ground via fence, ≤ 1.24 mm via pitch | ADRV9009 DS Rev B p115, Eq. 1 at 12 GHz, ER=4.1 |
| Trace width (indicative) | 5 mil (FR4, stripline) | ADRV9009 DS p113 Figure 444; recompute for final stackup |

**AC coupling caps (C21–C28):**
- Value: 100 nF (schematic)
- Package: 0201 (C_0201_0603Metric footprint)
- Placement: as close to J4 (FMC connector) as possible, away from J2 (JX2)
- Per ADRV9009 DS p113: "The ac coupling capacitors (100 nF) on these signals
  are placed near the connector and away from the chip to minimize coupling."
- Pad size must match trace width through cap; use smooth tapers if pad ≠ trace width.
- Both P and N caps for a given lane must be placed symmetrically to maintain
  intra-pair balance.

**TX lane path topology:**
```
J2 (JX2) → In2.Cu stripline → Cap (C2x) near J4 → short stub to J4 pin
```
Both segments (J2→cap and cap→J4) are impedance-controlled 100 Ω differential.

### 3.2 GTH Reference Clocks (2 pairs, 4 nets)

**Preferred routing layer: In2.Cu (same as JESD lanes, same reference planes).**

| Constraint | Value | Source |
|---|---|---|
| Zdiff | 100 Ω ± 10% | ADRV9009 DS Rev B p112 |
| Intra-pair skew | ≤ 5 mil | **[TO CONFIRM]** UG576 |
| Inter-clock length match | N/A (clocks are independent) | — |
| Reference plane | Unbroken GND on both adjacent layers | ADRV9009 DS p112 |
| AC coupling on carrier | None required (on SOM) | DEC-049; SOM schematic sheet 10 |
| Termination on carrier | None — FPGA GTH on-die, RCAL-calibrated | **[VERIFIED 2026-06-23]** UG576 v1.7.1 RX AFE (line 16313): calibrated internal termination resistors. Use Mode 1 AC-coupled (Table 4-3, line 16556): 800 mV internal, no external signal resistors. Table 5-9 PCB checklist (line 31192): only 100 nF AC caps listed for MGTHRXP/N and MGTHTXP/N; no external resistor rows. DS925 p421: RIN = 100 Ω internal. RCAL 100 Ω precision resistor is on SOM PCB — not carrier; correctly absent from carrier schematics. |
| Max trace length | Same as JESD: < 6 inches preferred | ADRV9009 DS p113 |
| Via count | Minimize | ADRV9009 DS p113 |

### 3.3 LVDS Sync / SYSREF Pairs (5 pairs, 10 nets)

**Preferred routing layer: In5.Cu (layer 5, signal).**
Rationale: These signals are Bank 65 LVCMOS18 LVDS at much lower frequency
than JESD lanes (SYSREF typically 1–10 MHz, SYNC at frame rate ~100 MHz).
Keeping them on In5.Cu separates them from the high-speed JESD lanes on In2.Cu
and reduces crosstalk. In5.Cu has In4.Cu (power) above and In6.Cu (GND) below;
the GND reference on In6.Cu is sufficient for LVDS at these frequencies.

Alternate: In2.Cu if routing congestion on In5.Cu, but keep LVDS signals
separated from JESD lane pairs (minimum 3× trace width clearance between groups).

| Constraint | Value | Source |
|---|---|---|
| Zdiff | 100 Ω ± 10% | Capture Guide §PCB Layout p8 |
| Intra-pair skew (P-N) | ≤ 5 mil (127 µm) | Capture Guide §PCB Layout p8 |
| Inter-pair length match | **[TO CONFIRM]** | JESD204B subclass 1 sysref timing; typically not required to match across pairs |
| Reference plane | GND on In6.Cu (below In5.Cu) | stackup DEC-053 |
| AC coupling on carrier | None | adrv9009_signals.sch |
| Trace width (indicative) | 3.5–4 mil (recompute for 8-layer stackup) | Capture Guide (4-layer FR4 baseline) |

Note on sysref (LA00_CC) and sysref_out (LA01_CC): these are GC-capable pins
(HP_DP_33_GC and HP_DP_32_GC in the FPGA). The CC (clock-capable) designation
means they can be connected to clock routing in the FPGA fabric; no additional
PCB constraint beyond standard LVDS differential impedance.

**Return-path rule — LVDS pairs on In5.Cu must not cross power-plane split
boundaries.**
In4.Cu (the reference plane above In5.Cu) is a power distribution layer with
splits between different supply rails. A trace crossing a split loses return-current
continuity on that plane, producing a return-path discontinuity and common-mode
noise injection into the LVDS pair. The impact on Zdiff is negligible at LVDS
frequencies; the constraint is about return-path integrity and EMI, not impedance.

Rule: Route all LVDS sync/sysref pairs over a continuous copper pour region on
In4.Cu, OR provide adjacent GND stitching vias to In6.Cu (the solid GND plane
below In5.Cu) bracketing any power-plane split that cannot be avoided. Preferred:
keep all LVDS routing within a single supply-domain region of In4.Cu.

